{"id":"2107.11702","submitter":"Ricard Alert","authors":"Ricard Alert, Alejandro Mart\\'inez-Calvo, Sujit S. Datta","title":"Cellular Sensing Governs the Stability of Chemotactic Fronts","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 128, 148101 (2022)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.128.148101","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.bio-ph cond-mat.soft nlin.PS q-bio.PE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In contexts ranging from embryonic development to bacterial ecology, cell\npopulations migrate chemotactically along self-generated chemical gradients,\noften forming a propagating front. Here, we theoretically show that the\nstability of such chemotactic fronts to morphological perturbations is\ndetermined by limitations in the ability of individual cells to sense and\nthereby respond to the chemical gradient. Specifically, cells at bulging parts\nof a front are exposed to a smaller gradient, which slows them down and\npromotes stability, but they also respond more strongly to the gradient, which\nspeeds them up and promotes instability. We predict that this competition leads\nto chemotactic fingering when sensing is limited at too low chemical\nconcentrations. Guided by this finding and by experimental data on E. coli\nchemotaxis, we suggest that the cells' sensory machinery might have evolved to\navoid these limitations and ensure stable front propagation. Finally, as\nsensing of any stimuli is necessarily limited in living and active matter in\ngeneral, the principle of sensing-induced stability may operate in other types\nof directed migration such as durotaxis, electrotaxis, and phototaxis.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 25 Jul 2021 00:08:36 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 5 Jun 2022 15:08:55 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-06-07"}
